Certainly! To check if a specific character is present in a given input string, you can use a simple approach in most programming languages. Here are examples in a few popular languages:

### Python
```python
def contains_character(input_string, character):
    return character in input_string

# Example usage
input_string = "Hello, World!"
character = "W"
if contains_character(input_string, character):
    print(f"The character '{character}' is present in the string.")
else:
    print(f"The character '{character}' is not present in the string.")
```

### JavaScript
```javascript
function containsCharacter(inputString, character) {
    return inputString.includes(character);
}

// Example usage
const inputString = "Hello, World!";
const character = "W";
if (containsCharacter(inputString, character)) {
    console.log(`The character '${character}' is present in the string.`);
} else {
    console.log(`The character '${character}' is not present in the string.`);
}
```

### Java
```java
public class CharacterCheck {
    public static boolean containsCharacter(String inputString, char character) {
        return inputString.indexOf(character) != -1;
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        String inputString = "Hello, World!";
        char character = 'W';
        if (containsCharacter(inputString, character)) {
            System.out.println("The character '" + character + "' is present in the string.");
        } else {
            System.out.println("The character '" + character + "' is not present in the string.");
        }
    }
}
```

### C++
```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <string>

bool containsCharacter(const std::string& inputString, char character) {
    return inputString.find(character) != std::string::npos;
}

int main() {
    std::string inputString = "Hello, World!";
    char character = 'W';
    if (containsCharacter(inputString, character)) {
        std::cout << "The character '" << character << "' is present in the string." << std::endl;
    } else {
        std::cout << "The character '" << character << "' is not present in the string." << std::endl;
    }
    return 0;
}
```

These snippets should help you check for the presence of a specific character in a string across different programming languages. Let me know if you need further assistance!
